Known properties of 3D WQOs 

Here we recall the physical properties of the
Wigner quantum oscillators  as given in .

The first thing we note is that the representation of
 was chosen such that,
as in the case of a 3D CQO, the
physical observables , ,  and  
are, in the case of the WQO, all
Hermitian operators within every Hilbert space  for each
 (in accordance with postulate P1 ).

Secondly, in the case of the WQO the Hamiltonian  is diagonal
in the basis ()-(),
i.e. the basis vectors  are
stationary states of the system. As in  the 3D CQO the energy
levels are equally spaced  with the same spacing .
Contrary to the CQO each Hilbert space  has no more
than four  equally spaced energy levels, with
spacing . More precisely,
     H p;= E_qp;  with  
     E_q=2 (3p-2q ).
So we can define stationary states  as superpositions of
states  with the same :
 
&& _0 = p;0,0,0, 3.2a  

&& _1 = (1,0,0)p;1,0,0+ (0,1,0)p;0,1,0+
(0,0,1)p;0,0,1, 3.2b  

&& _2 = (1,1,0)p;1,1,0+ (1,0,1)p;1,0,1+
(0,1,1)p;0,1,1, 3.2c  

&& _3 = p;1,1,1, 3.2d 
where  are complex numbers. The
stationary states satisfy . Only the
states with  belong to the space . Note that in
the atypical cases () the lowest energy level is
degenerate: there are three linearly independent states with the
same ground state energy.

Perhaps  the most striking difference between  the WQO and the
CQO is that the geometry of the Wigner oscillators is
non-commutative: the position operators , ,  of
the oscillating particle  do not commute with each other,
[_i,_j]0  for   ij=1,2,3.
Hence for the Wigner oscillators a coordinate representation
(-representation) does not exist . Similarly,
[_i,_j]0  for   ij=1,2,3
and therefore also a momentum representation (-representation)
cannot be defined .

The relations () and () imply that the WQO belongs to the class of
models of non-commutative quantum oscillators - 
and, more generally, to
theories with non-commutative geometry . The literature on this subject is
vast. Moreover the subject is not any longer of purely theoretical interest. Most
recently papers predicting (experimentally) measurable deviations from the
commutativity of the coordinates have been published -. 
Here however, we only deal with a purely theoretical description.

Following the non-commutativity, it is natural to ask about the nature
and value of the commutator 
(or , or ). The answer to this question is
relevant since it is used in the derivation of the uncertainty relations between the
coordinates for instance. 
To answer this, note that the commutators between the operators  and 
do not belong to the Lie superalgebra  
( and  are odd elements of the algebra),
so they cannot be rewritten in a simpler form.
Of course, one can compute the action of these commutators on basis
vectors of the considered  modules . 
We have actually made these computations. However the
resulting formulas are rather complicated. Later, we content ourselves
with just one illustrative example in ().

It is worth pointing out that the commutators ,
 and  are themselves operators that 
do not commute with each other in any one of the state
spaces ,  and therefore cannot be diagonalized simultaneously.
For this reason the non-commutativity between our position and momentum
operators is very different from the non-commutativity of generalized Heisenberg
commutation relations
[_i,_j]=i_ij ,[_i,_j]=i_ij ,[_i,_j]=i_ij   
often adopted in the literature on non-commutative quantum mechanics (see for instance
 -). In the right hand side of () 
and  are numbers (which are often further simplified, e.g.,
, , etc.) and therefore all operators
, ,  are simultaneously diagonal (in
any basis of the state space).

