The generalization of this result to any -state is evident:

 
If the system is in one of the -basis states
 then  measurements of
,  and  imply that  the oscillating particle can be
found  in  no more than 8 nests with coordinates
 r_1=p-q+_1 ,  r_2= p-q+_2 ,  
r_3=p-q+_3 ,
on a sphere with radius . The measured
values of the momenta can take also only 8 different values,
 p_1=p-q+_1 ,  p_2= p-q+_2 ,  
p_3=p-q+_3 .

Conclusion 2 significantly enhances the properties of the WQO
known so far, and collected in Conclusion 1. The particle is not
just anywhere on the sphere. In every -state  the
particle can be spotted in no more than 8 points of the sphere
with radius . This is what we can say so far. What we
cannot say yet is whether some of these nests are not
forbidden for "visits" or what is the probability of finding the
particle in any one of them.

In order to investigate this last question we
shall need the eigenvectors and the eigenvalues of all the operators
of the coordinates and of the momenta. Before that a short remark
related to the properties of any WQS will be in order.

Let  be an observable and let   be an
orthonormed basis of eigenvectors of : 
. Assume that the system  is in a state 
 normalized to 1. Postulate P2  tells us that the
expectation value  of the observable 
in the state  is
O _O )= _1^2 O_1++ _n^2 O_n.
It follows that  gives the probability of  measuring
the eigenvalue  of the operator .
This is just the superposition principle  of quantum mechanics. The conclusion
is that this principle holds for any WQS.

Thus in order to examine the probability for the particle to be
in one of the 8 nests, one has to introduce as a first step
an -basis, namely an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors of
  for any . The second step is to express the
-basis via the -basis for any , and to apply
the superposition principle.

One has to proceed in a similar way in order to examine the
probability for the particle to have each one of the possible
values of momentum.

Let us define, for any  and any 
