We see that the coefficients  of  and
 are equal up to a sign, and moreover their square
modulus is . Therefore the superposition principle asserts
that with equal probability 1/2 the first coordinate  of the
particle is either  or  . In other
words, the probability of finding the particle somewhere in the
four nests above the -plane is 1/2; and the probability to
find the particle somewhere in the four nests below the
-plane is also 1/2. Let us underline that this conclusion
is time independent. The time dependent basis which we have used
in order to derive it was playing only an intermediate role.

By means of the same arguments, using (),
() and (),
one concludes that also with probability  the second
coordinate  and the third coordinate  of the particle
take values  and , respectively
for the state .

Taking the three results (about the probabilities for ,
 and ) together does however not lead to a unique
solution for the probabilities to find the particle in a
particular nest.
Indeed, there are 8 probabilities to be
determined (one for each nest). From () we have deduced that
the sum of four of them (above the -plane) is 1/2, and the
sum of the remaining four (below the -plane) is also 1/2; so
this yields 2 linear relations for the 8 unknown probabilities.
Similarly, () and () each yield 2 linear relations. So
in total there are 6 linear relations in 8 unknowns. A more
detailed investigation even shows that only 4 of the 6 linear
relations are independent. This leads to the conclusion that the
probability of the particle being found in each nest cannot be
determined by the present considerations: there remain certain
degrees of freedom.

We have made this analysis for the example , but
from () it is clear that this conclusion generalizes to the
case of  all -states.
This follows from the fact that in the
inverse transformations () only two different vectors 
appear, each with a coefficient of which the square modulus is
1/2.

We summarize the results in the next proposition.

 
If the system is
in one of the -basis states  , then measurements of
the position of the oscillating particle  are such that it can
only be observed to occupy one of  the 8 nests with
coordinates
 r_k =p-q+_k ,  k=1,2,3,
on a sphere of dimensionless radius .
The probability  of finding  the
particle in the nest with coordinates
 cannot be determined. However, the
 probability of finding the particle somewhere in the four nests
with first coordinate equal to  is 1/2, and of  finding
it somewhere in the four nests with first coordinate equal to
 is also 1/2. The same holds for the second and third
coordinates.

The measurement of the momentum of the particle can take one of
the eight values
 p_k =p-q+_k ,  k=1,2,3.
Again, the individual probabilities for each of the eight
possible values of the momenta cannot be determined; but the
the probability of having  a fixed component  is 1/2, and
that of a fixed component  is also 1/2 ().

The proof of the second part of Proposition 2, related to the
probabilities of the 8 possible values () for the measurement
of the  momentum of the particle, is essentially the same as for
the coordinates. This time however, one has to use the orthonormal
basis of eigenvectors of , given by:
