Thus only the states  of the WQO and  of the
CQO have one and the same space dimensions. This is perhaps not
surprising since only these states have  one and the same energy
 (in units of ). The energy of the other
WQO states is 1, whereas for the other CQO states it is 5.


Concluding remarks) 

It is clear that while alternative, non-canonical solutions to the
compatibility equations () between Hamilton's equations and the
Heisenberg equations exist in our  WQO model, they are
in several very important respects quite different from the
canonical solutions.

Firstly, each state space  of our one particle 3D WQO is
finite-dimensional; 8-dimensional in the case of typical
representations of , and either  or -dimensional
in the case of atypical representations.

Secondly, both the energy and the angular momentum are quantized,
with equally spaced energy levels, all positive and with
separation , and with the angular momentum
restricted to be  or . Since there are only a finite number
of energy levels, the energy is bounded. The degeneracies are
always either  or . The lowest energy state is
non-degenerate in all the typical cases, but degenerate in each of
the atypical cases.

Thirdly, the spectrum of coordinates is also quantized, to the
extent that in any stationary state measurements of the
coordinates ,  and  give values consistent only
with the particle being found at a finite number of possible
sites, namely the various nests that we have identified. In the
typical,  case, the number of possible nests is , while
in the atypical cases it is  if  and only  if .
In all cases the distance of the particle from the origin is
bounded and may take on only the values
 with  such that
.

Fourthly, not only is the mean trajectory of the particle in any
stationary state zero, but there exist both typical and atypical
states for which the standard deviation of some coordinate ,
or some component of linear momentum , is also zero. This
implies that for the WQO there exists no uncertainty relation
involving a non-zero uncertainty parameter  that applies
to all states at all times.

Fifthly, the atypical case is distinguished from the typical case
in possessing stationary states of dimension lower than three,
namely two-dimensional in the case  and one-dimensional in
the case .

Many of these non-standard results are a consequence of the fact
that the underlying geometry of this WQO model is
non-commutative. This means that their interpretation must be
undertaken carefully. In particular it should be stressed that it
is not possible to specify precisely the position of the particle.
Fortunately, the square operators , 
and  not only mutually commute but also commute with the
Hamiltonian. Their common eigenstates are the stationary states
, for which the eigenvalues of , 
and  are simultaneously  fixed to be either ,  or .
Thus the spectrum of the measured values of each of the
coordinates themselves, ,  and , is necessarily
restricted to the set of values , 
and . Any measurement of a coordinate,  say,
results in one or other of the allowed positive or negative
values of  with, as we have shown, equal probability,
leaving the signs of the other coordinates undetermined. Thus the
particle in a stationary state  has a certain
probability of being within one or other of the relevant nests,
but it is not to be thought of as localized in any particular
nest.

In this article we have restricted ourselves to the relatively
simple case of an , single particle 3-dimensional WQO with a
relatively low, -dimensional Fock space  associated
with typical irreducible representations of , and even
lower dimensions for atypical representations. A very natural
next step is to generalize the results to the case of an -body
3-dimensional WQO as introduced in . In such a case the
dimension of the Fock space is -dimensional for typical
representations, and again lower dimensions for atypical
representations. The relevant calculations are somewhat intricate
and will be the subject of a separate article, in which the
restriction from the Lie superalgebra  to the simple Lie
algebra  of the rotation group plays a key role in the
determination of the possible angular momentum states of our
multiparticle system. It suffices to say at this stage that not
only are the energy and angular momentum quantized and bounded
but, in the corresponding stationary states of fixed energy and
angular momentum, so are the single particle coordinates and
components of linear momentum. As is to be expected the
corresponding nest structure is more complicated and we have to
contend with the relevant class  statistics, and account for
the numbers of particles whose coordinates, when measured, can
coincide with those of the nests, as well as more complicated
patterns of degeneracy.

Further generalizations also come to mind. In particular the
class of irreducible representations considered here are those
specified by the parameter . There exist other
finite-dimensional irreducible representations of , and
more generally of , that are specified not just by a
single positive integer , but by a partition or equivalently a
sequence of Kac-Dynkin indices . These can be expected to
provide other interesting models of the Wigner quantum oscillator
in the one-particle case and, more particularly, in
multi-particle cases. At the same time it would be interesting to
explore in the same way other non-oscillator Wigner quantum systems.
For examples of this kind see .



